      "officialText": "2025-26 3\nACADEMIC STANDARDS AND POLICIES\nGRADUATION REQUIREMENTS\n1. Students must successfully meet the District's minimum proficiency standards.\n2. Students must successfully complete 250 semester credits in grades 9-12.\n3. All students, unless otherwise noted, must successfully complete the following Riverdale High School\ncourses:\n (a) Social Science : Three one-year courses\n (b) English : Four one-year courses;\n (c) Mathematics : Three one-year courses;\n (d) Science : Three one-year courses\n Biology, Chemistry and Physics\n (e) Physical Education : Two one-year courses;\n (f) Fine Arts : One year course in, Art Appreciation, World Language, Music,\nor Drama;\n (g) Ethnic Studies : One semester course in Ethnic Studies beginning with the\nfreshman class of 2025-2026 (Class of 2029)\n (h) Freshman Requirement : One year of Freshman Studies (Ending at the conclusion of\n2027-2028 school year), Freshman Literacy or AVID 9\n (i) Personal Finance : One semester course in Personal Finance beginning with the\nfreshman class of 2027-2028 (Class of 2031)\n4. Graduating seniors must show documented evidence of application to a college or vocational school,\nproof of employment, evidence of 3 interviews for employment, or military enlistment.\nCREDITS NEEDED TO ADVANCE TO THE NEXT GRADE LEVEL\n 10th Grade/Sophomore Status ............................................................... Passed 60 Credits\n 11th Grade/Junior Status ...................................................................... Passed 120 Credits\n 12th Grade/Senior Status ..................................................................... Passed 180 Credits\nCERTIFICATE OF COMPLETION REQUIREMENTS\nAn individual with exceptional needs may be awarded a certificate of completion. (Education Code\n56390)\nTo obtain a certificate of completion, students may complete 250 credits including the following\nalternative course of study in grades 9-12, with each course being one year unless otherwise specified:\n1. Four courses in English\n2. Three courses in mathematics\n3. Three courses in science\n4. Three courses in social studies\n5. Two courses in physical education\n6. One freshman requirement course ending at the conclusion of the 2027-28 school year.",
