      "officialText": "2025-26 4\n7. One semester in Ethnic Studies beginning with the 2028-29 school year.\n8. One technology course ending at the conclusion of the 2024-25 school year\n9. One semester in Personal Finance beginning with the 2030-31 school year\n10. Additional elective coursework\nDELAYED ENROLLMENT\nAny continuing student who wishes to delay fall or spring enrollment without prior notification will be re -\nenrolled upon return. Students must un derstand that they may not be able to re -register for their same\nclasses due to the limited availability.\nSTUDENT ADVISEMENT\nStudent Advisement: “All students at Riverdale High School will meet with the College and Career\nCounselor or their assigned Assistant Principal and their parent, as needed, to discuss academics, career\ndecisions/choices, graduation requirements, college choices/entrance, scholarship applications,\nattendance and discipline. The College and Career Counselor is available to offer students\ninformation/guidance on post-secondary opportunities as well as grant and scholarship opportunities.\nGRADES AND REPORT CARDS\nProgress reports and final semester grades will be issued to students enrolled for more than 50% of the\nquarter, evaluating student achievement and proficiency in the academic subject areas. Student effort and\ncitizenship may also be evaluated.\nOfficial grades are based on the final semester grade. Progress reports will be mai led at the end of each\nquarter grading period as well as at each progress reporting period. This report will give the grade as it is\naccumulated to that point. Eligibility for extra -curricular activities (including dances) will be based on the\nquarter grade reports. Students will be declared ineligible if they are below a 2.0 G.P.A. and/or have one or\nmore failing grades.\nStudents may petition for eligibility during one quarter each school year.\nVALEDICTORIAN/SALUTATORIAN/HONOR CUP REQUIREMENTS\nG.P.A. is computed on grades earned from 9th through 12th grades, excluding Aide and Tutor course, , and\ngrades earned from schools that are not accredited. This G.P.A. calculation is used to determine\nValedictorian, Salutatorian, and students receiving Honor Cups . Honor Cups are determined by students\nwho have taken, or in progress of, 180 credits (equivalent to 36 – 5 credit courses) with a high “B” (3.5 GPA)\nor better [Low “A” (3.75 GPA) or better beginning with the Class of 2029 ] from College Prep courses\nincluding Honors and AP courses by the end of the 3rd quarter of their senior year. Seniors who graduate\nwith a .3.5 – 3.99 weighted grade point average will earn “Honors” and those with a 4.0 and above will earn\n“High Honors” designation at graduation.\n GRADE POINTS EARNED\n REGULAR COURSES HONORS/AP COURSES\n A = 4.00 A = 5.00\n B = 3.00 B = 4.00\n C = 2.00 C = 3.00\n D = 1.00 D = 1.00\n F = 0.00 F = 0.00\n\n2025-26 5\nAWARDS/ACADEMIC LETTER CRITERIA\nStudents accumulating a G.P.A. of 3.75 and above are eligible to receive an academic letter at the end of\neach year. Students earning a 3.5 GPA at the end of each quarter will earn Honor Roll recognition.\nGolden State Seal of Merit Diploma\nThe Golden State Seal Merit Diploma (GSSMD) insignia is awarded jointly by the State Board of\nEducation and the State Superintendent of Public Instruction to recognize students who have\ndemonstrated mastery of the high school curriculum in at least six subject areas. In order for students to\nqualify for this seal to be placed on their diploma, as per requirements set forth by the California\nDepartment of Education, they must have demonstrated mastery of the curriculum within at least six\nsubject areas: English Language Arts, Mathematics, Science, United States History, and two addition\nsubject areas. For more information on qualifying for this please see your academic counselor.\nCalifornia State Seal of Biliteracy\nThe state seal of Biliteracy was established to recognize high school graduates who have attained a high\nlevel of proficiency in speaking, reading, and writing in one or mor e languages in addition to English.\nStudents must demonstrate completion of all English language arts requirements for graduation with an\noverall GPA of 2.0 in these classes, passage of the CAASPP English language arts exam at or above the\n“standard met” a chievement level, proficiency in one or more languages as demonstrated through;\npassage of a world language advanced placement (AP) examination with a score of 3 or higher,\ncompletion of a 4 year high school course of study in a world language with an over all GPA of 3.0 or\nhigher in that course, passage of the SAT II world language examination. For more information on\nqualifying for this please see your academic counselor.\nTESTING AND CAREER CHOICE ASSISTANCE\nWhile enrolled at Riverdale High School, students are required to take various tests for a variety of reasons.\n All of these tests give both the student and assistant principal a better idea of the students’ interests,\naptitudes and abilities. A college and career counselor will also be available to assist students in the\ndevelopment of personal learning plans.\n EAP: The California State University (CSU) participates in the Early Assessment Program (EAP), an\nacademic preparation program to help high school students meet college -readiness standards i n\nEnglish language arts and mathematics before admission to a CSU campus. This test is given to 11th\ngrade students in the spring of their junior year as part of the Smarter Balanced Assessments.\n SMARTER BALANCED ASSESSMENTS : The Smarter Balanced Assess ment Consortium is\ndeveloping a system of valid, reliable, and fair next-generation assessments aligned to the Common\nCore State Standards (CCSS) in English language arts/literacy (ELA/literacy and mathematics for\ngrades 3-8 and 11. 11th grade students take these exams in the spring of their junior year.\n SAT/ACT: Seniors going to a four-year college may take the ACT or SAT (Scholastic Aptitude Test).\nThe PSAT test is for sophomores and juniors to prepare them for the SAT. It is suggested juniors take\nthe SAT in the spring of their junior year. Seniors planning to apply to a four -year college are\nencouraged to take the ACT or SAT. Seniors should check application requirements for four -year\ncolleges they plan to apply to.\n ELPAC: All students identif ied as English Learners (EL) are assessed to determine their level of\nEnglish proficiency.",
